alth care system.  Or ... we could feed them more fast food to force the fast food restaurants to create a more healthy menu.  The problem here is that the author's &quot;if/then&quot; logic is fallacious.  Convincing parents not to enroll their children in private schools will not mandate public schools to improve.   If that logic worked, public schools would have already improved!   Private schools are not exactly a new idea, after all.  They've been around a long time, and this seems to have had little effect on &quot;crappy public schools.&quot; So, let's say that hundreds or thousands of parents come to believe that they are &quot;bad&quot; for sending their kids to private school and enroll their students in public schools en masse.  What would this really do?  I can think of at least one immediate, inevitable effect.  An increased student population will crowd overcrowded classrooms and further strain most every resource in the public school system.  Now there's a positive solution!  (not) "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1279" language="en" documentId="3115" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="prolife and not ashamed" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:43PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="32" thumbsDown="0" origId="3115" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1279"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>